comments.body:
We had an array of delete_ids and update_ids where we (developers) used to look for which ids were updated or deleted. https://bibdata.princeton.edu/dumps/23916.json 
However this was not always the case and we had to look deeper in the index to confirm if some of the records were truly deleted or updated. 
This would come as a request from catalogers when blacklight would not reflect the record changes in voyager. I don't think that displaying the index status would resolve this issue and provide an answer to a cataloger who wants to see their changes in blacklight; 
Maybe this 'Status' view could be a first step but if the changes are not displaying in blacklight, the second step would be to open an issue in bibdata or ask in the catalog channel. 
I do think though that we should not proceed creating this feature without having a real user request.

comments.body:
@hackartisan no, they will show "Unavailable". As soon as the first JavaScript calls returns (and this is the "fast" API call) all records will have they availability updated (Available or Unavailable). 

I am about to push an update to this PR that will retry the Availability for "Unavailable" items with the slow API call. More to follow.

I've pushed a new commit that has the retry logic (via the slow-ish API call) for Unavailable items. This will keep the same user experience as our original design, but the slow API call will __not__ block the initial display of Available/Unavailable items. 

The only thing that might be disconcerting to the user is that if an item is Unavailable initially but then we recognize that  it's available through CDL they will see the availability badge toggle from "Unavailable" to "Available" once the slow-ish call returns. Not ideal but not horrible either, particularly since the toggle will only happen for those (few?) items in CDL that were reported as Unavailable in the first call.

[![Coverage Status](https://coveralls.io/builds/41793931/badge)](https://coveralls.io/builds/41793931)

Coverage decreased (-0.07%) to 96.842% when pulling **724d268e23045170d324f3ec8ef24982c635e254 on availability_speed_improvement** into **1bd9fcd0dcd29c2593c47676df884e2dd3f544d6 on main**.

I've reverted the code to make to make the second call in the Search page. 

The only second call to bibdata will happend in the *show* page if the record is unavailable according to Alma (the idea being that on the second call will ask bibdata to check deeper to see if it is available via CDL.)

Still pending to update the test suite to match the new code path.
